messages.kbn.advancedSettings.context.tieBreakerF: A comma-separated list of fields to use for tie-breaking between documents that have the same timestamp value. From this list the first field that is present and sortable in the current index pattern is used.
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.courier.batchSearch:
When disabled, dashboard panels will load individually, and search requests will terminate when users navigate
           away or update the query. When enabled, dashboard panels will load together when all of the data is loaded, and
           searches will not terminate.
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.courier.ignoreFilte: This configuration enhances support for dashboards containing visualizations accessing dissimilar indexes. When disabled, all filters are applied to all visualizations. When enabled, filter(s) will be ignored for a visualization when the visualization's index does not contain the filtering field.
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.courier.maxRequests: Controls the {maxRequestsLink} setting used for _msearch requests sent by Kibana. Set to 0 to disable this config and use the Elasticsearch default.
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.courier.requestPref:
Allows you to set which shards handle your search requests.
  • {sessionId}: restricts operations to execute all search requests on the same shards. This has the benefit of reusing shard caches across requests.
  • {custom}: allows you to define a your own preference. Use courier:customRequestPreference to customize your preference value.
  • {none}: means do not set a preference. This might provide better performance because requests can be spread across all shard copies. However, results might be inconsistent because different shards might be in different refresh states.
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.csv.quoteValuesText: Should values be quoted in csv exports?
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.csv.separatorText: Separate exported values with this string
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.darkModeText: Enable a dark mode for the Kibana UI. A page refresh is required for the setting to be applied.
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.dateFormat.dayOfWee: What day should weeks start on?

kbn.advancedSettings.dateFormat.scaledTe.text: Values that define the format used in situations where time-based data is rendered in order, and formatted timestamps should adapt to the interval between measurements. Keys are {intervalsLink}.

messages.kbn.advancedSettings.dateFormat.timezone: Which timezone should be used. {defaultOption} will use the timezone detected by your browser.

kbn.advancedSettings.dateFormatText.text: When displaying a pretty formatted date, use this {formatLink}

messages.kbn.advancedSettings.dateNanosFormatText: Used for the {dateNanosLink} datatype of Elasticsearch
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.defaultColumnsText: Columns displayed by default in the Discovery tab
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.defaultIndexText: The index to access if no index is set
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.defaultRoute.defaul: This setting specifies the default route when opening Kibana. You can use this setting to modify the landing page when opening Kibana. The route must start with a slash ("/").
The route must start with a slash ("/")
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.disableAnimationsTe: Turn off all unnecessary animations in the Kibana UI. Refresh the page to apply the changes.
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.discover.aggsTermsS: Determines how many terms will be visualized when clicking the "visualize" button, in the field drop downs, in the discover sidebar.
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.discover.sampleSize: The number of rows to show in the table
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.discover.searchOnPa: Controls whether a search is executed when Discover first loads. This setting does not have an effect when loading a saved search.
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.discover.sortDefaul: Controls the default sort direction for time based index patterns in the Discover app.
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.docTableHideTimeCol: Hide the 'Time' column in Discover and in all Saved Searches on Dashboards.
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.docTableHighlightTe: Highlight results in Discover and Saved Searches Dashboard. Highlighting makes requests slow when working on big documents.
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.fieldsPopularLimitT: The top N most popular fields to show
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.format.defaultTypeM: Map of the format name to use by default for each field type. {defaultFormat} is used if the field type is not mentioned explicitly
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.histogram.barTarget: Attempt to generate around this many bars when using "auto" interval in date histograms
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.histogram.maxBarsTe: Never show more than this many bars in date histograms, scale values if needed
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.historyLimitText: In fields that have history (e.g. query inputs), show this many recent values
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.indexPattern.recent: For index patterns containing timestamps in their names, look for this many recent matching patterns from which to query the field mapping
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.indexPatternPlaceho: The placeholder for the "Index pattern name" field in "Management > Index Patterns > Create Index Pattern".
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.maxBucketsText: The maximum number of buckets a single datasource can return
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.maxCellHeightText: The maximum height that a cell in a table should occupy. Set to 0 to disable truncation
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.metaFieldsText: Fields that exist outside of _source to merge into our document when displaying it
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.notifications.banne: The time in milliseconds which a banner notification will be displayed on-screen for. Setting to {infinityValue} will disable the countdown.

kbn.advancedSettings.notifications.banne.text: A custom banner intended for temporary notices to all users. {markdownLink}.

messages.kbn.advancedSettings.notifications.error: The time in milliseconds which an error notification will be displayed on-screen for. Setting to {infinityValue} will disable.
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.notifications.infoL: The time in milliseconds which an information notification will be displayed on-screen for. Setting to {infinityValue} will disable.
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.notifications.warni: The time in milliseconds which a warning notification will be displayed on-screen for. Setting to {infinityValue} will disable.
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.pinFiltersText: Whether the filters should have a global state (be pinned) by default
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.query.allowWildcard: When set, * is allowed as the first character in a query clause. Currently only applies when experimental query features are enabled in the query bar. To disallow leading wildcards in basic lucene queries, use {queryStringOptionsPattern}.

kbn.advancedSettings.query.queryStringOp.text: {optionsLink} for the lucene query string parser. Is only used when "{queryLanguage}" is set to {luceneLanguage}.

messages.kbn.advancedSettings.savedObjects.listin: Number of objects to fetch for the listing pages
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.savedObjects.perPag: Number of objects to show per page in the load dialog
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.searchQueryLanguage: Query language used by the query bar. KQL is a new language built specifically for Kibana.
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.shortenFieldsText: Shorten long fields, for example, instead of foo.bar.baz, show f.b.baz
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.storeUrlText: The URL can sometimes grow to be too large for some browsers to handle. To counter-act this we are testing if storing parts of the URL in session storage could help. Please let us know how it goes!
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.suggestFilterValues: Set this property to false to prevent the filter editor from suggesting values for fields.

kbn.advancedSettings.suggestFilterValues.comment: "Filter editor" refers to the UI you create filters in.

kbn.advancedSettings.timepicker.quickRan.text: The list of ranges to show in the Quick section of the time filter. This should be an array of objects, with each object containing "from", "to" (see {acceptedFormatsLink}), and "display" (the title to be displayed).

messages.kbn.advancedSettings.timepicker.timeDefa: The timefilter selection to use when Kibana is started without one
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.visualization.color: Maps values to specified colors within visualizations
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.visualization.dimmi: The opacity of the chart items that are dimmed when highlighting another element of the chart. The lower this number, the more the highlighted element will stand out. This must be a number between 0 and 1.
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.visualization.heatm: The maximum number of buckets a single datasource can return. A higher number might have negative impact on browser rendering performance
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.visualization.loadi: Time to wait before dimming visualizations during query
messages.kbn.advancedSettings.visualization.showR: Whether the region map shows a warning when terms cannot be joined to a shape on the map.

kbn.advancedSettings.visualization.tileM.text: The maximum geoHash precision displayed on tile maps: 7 is high, 10 is very high, 12 is the max. {cellDimensionsLink}
Default {propertiesLink} for the WMS map server support in the coordinate map

messages.kbn.advancedSettings.visualizeEnableLabs:
Allows users to create, view, and edit experimental visualizations. If disabled,
          only visualizations that are considered production-ready are available to the user.

messages.kbn.common.tutorials.premCloudInstructio:
Go to [Elastic Cloud]({link}). Register if you do not already have an account. Free 14-day trial available.

Log into the Elastic Cloud console

To create a cluster, in Elastic Cloud console:
 1. Select **Create Deployment** and specify the **Deployment Name**
 2. Modify the other deployment options as needed (or not, the defaults are great to get started)
 3. Click **Create Deployment**
 4. Wait until deployment creation completes
 5. Go to the new Cloud Kibana instance and follow the Kibana Home instructions

If you are running this Kibana instance against a hosted Elasticsearch instance, proceed with manual setup.

Save the **Elasticsearch** endpoint as {urlTemplate} and the cluster **Password** as {passwordTemplate} for your records

messages.kbn.server.tutorials.apm.dotNetClient.do:
Add the the agent package(s) from [NuGet]({allNuGetPackagesLink}) to your .NET application. There are multiple       NuGet packages available for different use cases. 

For an ASP.NET Core application with Entity Framework       Core download the [Elastic.Apm.NetCoreAll]({netCoreAllApmPackageLink}) package. This package will automatically add every       agent component to your application. 

 In case you would like to to minimize the dependencies, you can use the       [Elastic.Apm.AspNetCore]({aspNetCorePackageLink}) package for just       ASP.NET Core monitoring or the [Elastic.Apm.EfCore]({efCorePackageLink}) package for just Entity Framework Core monitoring. 

       In case you only want to use the public Agent API for manual instrumentation use the [Elastic.Apm]({elasticApmPackageLink}) package.

messages.kbn.server.tutorials.ems.downloadStepTex:
1. Navigate to Elastic Maps Service [landing page]({emsLandingPageUrl}).
2. In the left sidebar, select an administrative boundary.
3. Click `Download GeoJSON` button.
messages.kbn.server.tutorials.ems.longDescription: [Elastic Maps Service (EMS)](https://www.elastic.co/elastic-maps-service) hosts tile layers and vector shapes of administrative boundaries. Indexing EMS administrative boundaries in Elasticsearch allows for search on boundary property fields.

messages.kbn.server.tutorials.ems.uploadStepText:
1. Open [Elastic Maps]({newMapUrl}).
2. Click `Add layer`, then select `Upload GeoJSON`.
3. Upload the GeoJSON file and click `Import file`.

messages.kbn.server.tutorials.redisLogs.longDescr: The `redis` Filebeat module parses error and slow logs created by Redis. For Redis to write error logs, make sure the `logfile` option, from the Redis configuration file, is set to `redis-server.log`. The slow logs are read directly from Redis via the `SLOWLOG` command. For Redis to record slow logs, make sure the `slowlog-log-slower-than` option is set. Note that the `slowlog` fileset is experimental. [Learn more]({learnMoreLink}).

messages.timelion.help.configuration.notValid.par: If you're using Logstash, you don't need to configure anything to start exploring your log data with Timelion. To search other indices, go to {advancedSettingsPath} and configure the {esDefaultIndex} and {esTimefield} settings to match your indices.
You'll also see some other Timelion settings. For now, you don't need to worry about them. Later, you'll see that you can set most of them on the fly if you need to.

for information about configuring the Elasticsearch datasource.

messages.timelion.help.configuration.valid.paragr: You should already see one chart, but you might need to make a couple adjustments before you see any interesting data:
Now, you should see a line chart that displays a count of your data points over time.
messages.timelion.help.configuration.valid.timeRa: Use the timepicker in the Kibana toolbar to select the time period that contains the data you want to visualize. Make sure you select a time period that includes all or part of the time range shown above.
messages.timelion.help.configuration.validTitle: Good news, Elasticsearch is configured correctly!
messages.timelion.help.dataTransforming.paragraph: Now that you've mastered the basics, it's time to unleash the power of Timelion. Let's figure out what percentage some subset of our data represents of the whole, over time. For example, what percentage of our web traffic comes from the US?
First, we need to find all events that contain US: {esUsQuery}.
Next, we want to calculate the ratio of US events to the whole. To divide {us} by everything, we can use the {divide} function: {divideDataQuery}.
Not bad, but this gives us a number between 0 and 1. To convert it to a percentage, simply multiply by 100: {multiplyDataQuery}.

Now we know what percentage of our traffic comes from the US, and can see how it has changed over time! Timelion has a number of built-in arithmetic functions, such as {sum}, {subtract}, {multiply}, and {divide}. Many of these can take a series or a number. There are also other useful data transformation functions, such as {movingaverage}, {abs}, and {derivative}.

timelion.help.dataTransforming.paragraph.text: Now that you're familiar with the syntax, refer to the

to see how to use all of the available Timelion functions. You can view the reference at any time by clicking \{Docs\} in the Kibana toolbar. To get back to this tutorial, click the \{Tutorial\} link at the top of the reference.

messages.timelion.help.querying.passingArgumentsT: Timelion has a number of shortcuts that make it easy to do common things. One is that for simple arguments that don't contain spaces or special characters, you don't need to use quotes. Many functions also have defaults. For example, {esEmptyQuery} and {esStarQuery} do the same thing. Arguments also have names, so you don't have to specify them in a specific order. For example, you can enter {esLogstashQuery} to tell the Elasticsearch datasource {esIndexQueryDescription}.
messages.timelion.help.welcome.content.paragraph1: Timelion is the clawing, gnashing, zebra killing, pluggable time series interface for {emphasizedEverything}. If your datastore can produce a time series, then you have all of the awesome power of Timelion at your disposal. Timelion lets you compare, combine, and combobulate datasets across multiple datasources with one easy-to-master expression syntax. This tutorial focuses on Elasticsearch, but you'll quickly discover that what you learn here applies to any datasource Timelion supports.
